    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/rh-index-comparison-primary",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary RH index comparison — CFD vs. in vitro hemolysis at five operating points",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/hemolysis-experimental-cpb-2023",
      "description": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) was compared against in vitro measurements for five flow-speed combinations (3–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). The simulation campaign was executed using ANSYS Fluent 2023R1 on a 4.2-million-element polyhedral mesh with the SST k-ω turbulence closure and the Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model. Boundary conditions were set to match the ISO 10628 test loop configuration. Predicted RH values ranged from 0.71 to 0.94 across all operating points, remaining below the acceptance threshold of RH < 1 in every case. Mean absolute error relative to experimental measurements was 6.3 %, within the ±10 % acceptance band defined in the V&V plan. The worst-case operating point (6 L/min, 3500 RPM) yielded RH = 0.94 experimentally and 0.89 computationally, a 5.3 % under-prediction attributable to near-wall shear resolution at the impeller tip. The analyst team reviewed residual convergence logs, mesh-independence data, and turbulence sensitivity runs before finalising this result. All supporting simulation files and post-processing scripts are archived in the project repository under revision tag v3.2.1.",
      "outcomeValue": "0.89",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "RH < 1.0 at all five operating points; mean absolute error < 10 % relative to experimental reference",
      "passed": true
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/mesh-independence-check",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh independence verification — shear stress convergence",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/fda-pump-geometry-v2",
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": "https://uofa.net/morrison/activity/mesh-refinement-study-2024",
      "description": "Three mesh densities (2.1 M, 4.2 M, 8.6 M elements) were evaluated for volume-averaged shear stress and RH index. Richardson extrapolation yielded a GCI of 1.8 % between the medium and fine meshes, confirming that the 4.2 M element mesh is adequate for production runs.",
      "outcomeValue": "GCI 1.8 %",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI < 5 % between medium and fine mesh",
      "passed": true
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/turbulence-sensitivity",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Turbulence model sensitivity — SST k-ω vs. realizable k-ε",
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": "https://uofa.net/morrison/activity/turbulence-sensitivity-study-2024",
      "description": "Two turbulence closures were compared at the nominal operating point (4.5 L/min, 2800 RPM). RH predictions differed by less than 3 % between models, confirming that the SST k-ω selection does not introduce material model-form uncertainty at MRL 2.",
      "outcomeValue": "Δ RH < 3 %",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model sensitivity < 5 % on RH",
      "passed": true
    }
  ],
